04921nam a22005535i 9780822390763DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223907637 a10.1515/97808223907632doi  a(DE-B1597)553697  a(OCoLC)1224278278  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE169.12b.W395 2009 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a973.922221 aWegner, Philip E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife between Two Deaths, 1989-2001 :bU.S. Culture in the Long Nineties /cPhilip E. Wegner; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b18 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents​ -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Present as a Moment of Danger -- tOne The Two Deaths of the 1990s -- tTwo October 3, 1951, to September II , 2001 Periodizing the Cold War in Don DeLillo's Underworld -- tThree I'll Be Back Repetitions and Revisions in the Terminator Films -- tFour A Fine Tradition The Remaking of the United States in Cape Fear -- tFive Where the Prospective Horizon Is Omitted Naturalism, Dystopia, and Politics in Fight Club and Ghost Dog -- tSix A Nightmare on the Brain of the Living Messianic Historicity, Alienations, and Independence Day -- tSeven As Many as Possible , Thin kin g as Much as Possible Figures of the Multitude in Joe Haldeman's Forever Trilogy -- tEight We 're Family Monstrous Kinships, Fidelity, and the Event in Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Octavia Butler's Parable Novels -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough virtuoso readings of significant works of American film, television, and fiction, Phillip E. Wegner demonstrates that the period between the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989 and the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001 fostered a unique consciousness and represented a moment of immense historical possibilities now at risk of being forgotten in the midst of the "war on terror." Wegner argues that 9/11 should be understood as a form of what Jacques Lacan called the "second death," an event that repeats an earlier "fall," in this instance the collapse of the Berlin Wall. By describing 9/11 as a repetition, Wegner does not deny its significance. Rather, he argues that it was only with the fall of the towers that the symbolic universe of the Cold War was finally destroyed and a true "new world order," in which the United States assumed disturbing new powers, was put into place.Wegner shows how phenomena including the debate on globalization, neoliberal notions of the end of history, the explosive growth of the Internet, the efflorescence of new architectural and urban planning projects, developments in literary and cultural production, new turns in theory and philosophy, and the rapid growth of the antiglobalization movement came to characterize the long nineties. He offers readings of some of the most interesting cultural texts of the era: Don DeLillo's White Noise; Joe Haldeman's Forever trilogy; Octavia Butler's Parable novels; the Terminator films; the movies Fight Club, Independence Day, Cape Fear, and Ghost Dog; and the television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer. In so doing, he illuminates fundamental issues concerning narrative, such as how beginnings and endings are recognized and how relationships between events are constructed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aNineteen nineties. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocab